               <desc type="building-data" source="#bibl000124-1">The sutra preservation hall or sutra repository (藏经殿)  of Anchansi is built on a brick foundation. The front façade is 3-bays wide and the depth is 3-bays. The central bay is twice as wide as the side bays. It has a single eaves hip-gable roof, and the gray rooftiles are punctuated with a central diamond of yellow and green glazed tiles. Under the eaves are four layer bracket sets (<term ref="/keyword/k000013">puzuo</term>) with a single <term ref="/keyword/k000172">huagong</term> and a locust head style ("insect head" or “grasshopper head” (fuzong tou 蜉䗥頭; mazhatou 螞蚱頭)) <term ref="/keyword/k000220">shuatou</term>. There is one intercolumnar bracket set in the central bay. The entasis of the pillars is clearly evident, making it possible to consider them "shuttle-shaped pillars" (suozhu 梭柱). The original system of woodwork/latticework is no longer extant.</desc>
